******
[5] Lithuania: updated governmental measures
Date: Wed 29 Jan 2014
Source: PigProgress [edited]
http://www.pigprogress.net/Health-Diseases/Outbreaks/2014/1/Lithuania-is-struggling-with-ASF-1453329W/


Lithuania intends to reduce the population of wild boars in the country from the current 60 000 to only 6000 in a bid to stop the spread of African swine fever (ASF), said the Interior Minister, Daylis Alfonsas Barakauskas, after a meeting with the government [see responses in items 1 and 2 above].

"Such a decision can be considered as a preventive measure aimed to avoid damage from ASF virus that could be huge. Its main carriers are wild boars, and there is no vaccine against ASF," said the report.

Barakauskas also said he plans to requests funds from the European Commission for the construction of a fence on the border with Belarus, which will be intended to prevent the migration of wild boars.

According to the head of the Lithuanian Veterinary and Food Service, Jonas Milius, the amount of funds requested for the construction of a fence is 15 million Lithuanian litas (EUR 4.3 million/USD 5.87 million). He also added that about 800 000 litas (EUR 250 000/USD 341 000) will be needed for the purchasing of mobile equipment for incineration of carcasses of wild boars.

"We hope that we will quickly eliminate the outbreak, and the movement of wild boars will not be very large, they usually settle in the winter," said Milius. Meanwhile, Ukraine announced that it stopped all pork imports from Lithuania, including pork products.

[Byline: Vladislav Vorontnikov]

--
Communicated by:
